<div class="textwrapper">
    <p><em>We are a gallery located in Hanover.</em></p>
    
    <p>Our aim is to produce art depicting a wide range of different viewpoints and concepts, as well as creating a gallery where we will try to bring your visual experience along."</p>
    
    
        <!--pulls a random 1000x1600 picture from unslash and displays it-->
    <img class=image src="https://source.unsplash.com/1000x1600/?gallery" alt="a gallery" title="Isn't this beautiful? Sadly, it's not our gallery." style="float:right;margin-left:30px">
    
    
    <p>A new version of the gallery, which was first announced in the January 2014 issue, will feature full-page spreads for two images of the famous portrait of Jesus, and they'll feature the same kind of text from the original art.</p>
    
    <p>"We are delighted to be working with A-Works, with which the company is currently developing the exhibition, and are very excited to collaborate with them to give A-Works access to the frescoes from that era. The frescoes are used recreations of classical art, with their own elements that we are always looking at at these exhibitions."</p>
    
    <p>While the artwork is not intended to be anything the standard gallery exhibits would never have had, the exhibition's purpose will remain to display the frescaes for all to see.</p>
    
    <p>This version of the first part is in the same condition as the original, and contains the frescoes.</p>
    
        <!--pulls a random 1000x1600 picture and displays it-->
    <img class=image src="https://source.unsplash.com/500x800/?gallery" alt="a gallery" title="You guessed it, this isn't our gallery either." style="float: left;margin-right:30px">
    
    <p>And while not the only artwork displayed at this exhibition is that of The Vamps from L'Enferior, as well as both of the original artwork and the frescoes from the original, there's also an artist's piece from the two frescoes from the 17th century, that actually features the frescos from the original.</p>
    
    <p>And while the frescoes do include very significant figures (see the next figure), it's not just the frescos that actually do represent the actual work by them.</p>
    
    <p>And there's also some pretty fascinating figures in this gallery, all of which are being featured here in this exhibition. But this is more about the art and not just the work, I'd love to see all of these figures being shown during this exhibition. The first thing that I really want to do here is to showcase different aspects of the artwork – and the art that we have created for. And I'll say this with the rest of the gallery – I love the way the art in which artists work is not solely dependent upon a single person, but upon their audience.</p>
    
    <p>The two frescoes on display are The D-10 and The D-27 from the 15th century, both of which have this very beautiful engravings, which you could call an artistic legacy in this very particular time. And although one of those engravings was drawn from a rather large scale, all of the sculptures and paintings have been made in an entirely new way.</p>

